    return $this->deny($actor, $action, $resourceType, $resourceId, 'role_denied');
}
```

3. **Resource Policy Layer**: Verify relationship between user and specific resource
```php
$policy = $this->policyHandlers[$resourceType];
$result = $policy->evaluate($actor, $action, $resourceId, $context);
```

**Additional Protections**:
- **Permission caching**: Reduces database load while maintaining security (short TTL)
- **Comprehensive audit logging**: Every authorization decision is logged with full context for forensics
- **Timing metrics**: Track authorization performance to detect anomalies
- **Self-action protection**: Prevent users from deleting themselves or escalating their own privileges
- **Attribute-based rules**: Support complex policies like "HR can only access their department"
- **Centralized enforcement**: All authorization goes through one service, ensuring consistency
- **Rate limiting integration**: Combine with rate limiting to prevent enumeration attacks
- **Fail-secure default**: If no policy matches, access is denied

No, hiding UI elements is **not security** - it's merely obscurity. Attackers can directly call your API endpoints regardless of what the UI shows. This is called "Missing Function Level Access Control" and was the root cause of the 2022 Optus breach that exposed 9.8 million customer records.

**VULNERABLE CODE**:

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Linq;

namespace VulnerableApp.Controllers
{
    [ApiController]
    [Route("api/[controller]")]
    public class UsersController : ControllerBase
    {
        private readonly IUserRepository _userRepository;

        public UsersController(IUserRepository userRepository)
        {
            _userRepository = userRepository;
        }

        // VULNERABLE: No authorization check - anyone can access
        [HttpGet("admin/all-users")]
        public IActionResult GetAllUsers()
        {
            // Assumes UI hides this from non-admins - WRONG!
            var users = _userRepository.GetAllUsersWithSensitiveData();
            return Ok(users);
        }

        // VULNERABLE: No authorization - relies on "hidden" URL
        [HttpDelete("admin/delete/{userId}")]
        public IActionResult DeleteUser(int userId)
        {
            _userRepository.DeleteUser(userId);
            return Ok(new { message = "User deleted" });
        }

        // VULNERABLE: Admin password reset without auth check
        [HttpPost("admin/reset-password/{userId}")]
        public IActionResult ResetUserPassword(int userId, [FromBody] PasswordResetDto dto)
        {
            _userRepository.SetPassword(userId, dto.NewPassword);
            return Ok(new { message = "Password reset successful" });
        }
    }
}
```

**Attack Payload**:
```bash
# Direct API call bypassing UI - no authentication required
curl -X GET https://api.example.com/api/users/admin/all-users

# Delete any user account
curl -X DELETE https://api.example.com/api/users/admin/delete/1

# Reset admin password to attacker-controlled value
curl -X POST https://api.example.com/api/users/admin/reset-password/1 \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"newPassword": "hacked123"}'
```

**Why This Is Dangerous**:
- UI-based security can be bypassed with tools like curl, Postman, or browser dev tools
- No server-side validation of user permissions
- Attackers can enumerate and access all admin functions by guessing URLs
- Similar to Optus breach where unauthenticated API exposed millions of records

